{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1029a8df-1781-4830-8676-00ab0ca3b282","content":"Here's how to migrate from `VSTest@3` to Microsoft.Testing.Platform while keeping TRX + code coverage:\n\n## 1. Update your test project\n\nIn your `.csproj`, add:\n\n```xml\n<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n```\n\n## 2. Replace `VSTestRunner@3` with `dotnet test`\n\nMicrosoft.Testing.Platform doesn't use `vstest.console.exe`, so `VSTest@3` won't work. Use a `DotNetCoreCLI@2` task (or a script) instead:\n\n```yaml\n# Before (VSTest@3)\n- task: VSTest@3\n  inputs:\n    testAssemblyVer2: '**/*Tests.dll'\n    resultsFolder: $(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults\n    codeCoverageEnabled: true\n\n# After (Microsoft.Testing.Platform via dotnet test)\n- task: DotNetCoreCLI@2\n  displayName: 'Run tests'\n  inputs:\n    command: test\n    projects: '**/*Tests.csproj'\n    arguments: >-\n      --results-directory $(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults\n      --logger trx\n      --collect \"Code Coverage\"\n```\n\n## 3. Publish results & coverage\n\n```yaml\n- task: PublishTestResults@2\n  displayName: 'Publish TRX results'\n  condition: always()\n  inputs:\n    testResultsFormat: VSTest\n    testResultsFiles: '$(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults/**/*.trx'\n\n- task: PublishCodeCoverageResults@2\n  displayName: 'Publish code coverage'\n  condition: always()\n  inputs:\n    summaryFileLocation: '$(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults/**/*.cobertura.xml'\n```\n\n> For Cobertura output, add package `coverlet.collector` or use `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=Cobertura\"` (Microsoft collector).\n\n## Key differences\n\n| | VSTest@3 | Microsoft.Testing.Platform |\n|---|---|---|\n| Runner | `vstest.console.exe` | Built into test binary |\n| Invocation | DLL-based | `dotnet test` on `.csproj` |\n| TRX | Built-in | `--logger trx` |\n| Coverage | `codeCoverageEnabled` | `--collect \"Code Coverage\"` |\n| Result publish | Auto | Separate `PublishTestResults@2` step |\n\nThe critical change is that `VSTest@3` **cannot** run Microsoft.Testing.Platform tests — you **must** switch to `dotnet test` (or run the test executable directly).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4493228e-7e21-4bf2-8060-ceb443d8ca38","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory seems empty. This is a general question about migrating from VSTest@3 to Microsoft.Testing.Platform in Azure Pipelines. Let me provide guidance based on my knowledge.","outputTokens":707,"requestId":"E842:15FC40:2726682:299C70A:6A0493AF"},"id":"f53ab9a2-31e3-4d1b-ae37-68ffc423b36e","timestamp":"2026-05-13T15:07:41.882Z","parentId":"a236a520-a408-4e88-947c-8f20bc80094c"}
